Indeed yes, at least for formatted string literals https://docs.python.org/3/whatsnew/3.6.html#whatsnew36-pep498.

Installed flake8 with pip (on Python 3).
python3 -m flake8 --bug-report
{
  "dependencies": [
    {
      "dependency": "setuptools",
      "version": "32.2.0"
    }
  ],
  "platform": {
    "python_implementation": "CPython",
    "python_version": "3.6.0",
    "system": "Darwin"
  },
  "plugins": [
    {
      "plugin": "mccabe",
      "version": "0.5.3"
    },
    {
      "plugin": "pycodestyle",
      "version": "2.2.0"
    },
    {
      "plugin": "pyflakes",
      "version": "1.3.0"
    }
  ],
  "version": "3.2.1"
}

Running against Python code containing new f-string, e.g.
```
name = 'John'
age = 30
my_string = f"He said his name is {name} and he is {age} years old."
```
... results a stack trace ending with "AttributeError: 'FlakesChecker' object has no attribute 'JOINEDSTR' ".

This is fixed in pyflakes 1.4.0 (https://github.com/PyCQA/pyflakes/blob/master/NEWS.txt).
